    <section class="wrap hero">
      <div>
        <p class="kicker">Builders</p>
        <h1>How to Choose an ADU Builder (2025 Checklist)</h1>
        <p class="subhead">Ten questions to find the right prefab, panelized, design-build, or GC partner—without drama or surprise costs.</p>
        <div class="cta">
          <a class="btn primary" href="/estimate" aria-label="Get matched to vetted ADU builders via estimate form">Get matched to vetted builders →</a>
          <a class="btn secondary" href="/builders" aria-label="See builder types and directory">See builder types</a>
        </div>
        <div class="progress" role="progressbar" aria-label="ADU journey progress (Costs → Regulations → Builders → Financing)" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100" aria-valuenow="75">
          <div class="progress__bar" style="width:75%"></div>
        </div>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>Table of contents</summary>
          <nav class="nav-inline" aria-label="On-page">
            <a href="#checklist">10-point checklist</a>
            <a href="#compare">Prefab vs custom: quick compare</a>
            <a href="#signals">Signals of a solid builder</a>
            <a href="#bids">How to run bids</a>
            <a href="#cases">Mini case studies</a>
            <a href="#faq">FAQ</a>
          </nav>
        </details>
        <div class="tldr" id="tldr">
          You’ll pick faster and avoid cost creep by aligning scope, allowances, and utility assumptions up front. Use this 10-point checklist with two or three builders, then lock a draw schedule and change-order rules before deposits.
        </div>
      </div>
      <figure>
        <img src="/assets/hero-adu.jpg" alt="Primary home and detached ADU connected by landscaped path" />
        <figcaption class="note">Context matters: site access, utilities, and setbacks influence the “right” builder type.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap" id="checklist">
      <h2>The 10-point ADU builder checklist</h2>
      <div class="card checklist">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Scope clarity</strong> — One page that says what is in vs out <span class="badge">baseline</span></li>
          <li><strong>Allowances</strong> — Cabinets, fixtures, appliances, flooring with realistic $/unit and brands</li>
          <li><strong>Exclusions</strong> — Landscaping, fences, window coverings, tap fees, trenching beyond X ft</li>
          <li><strong>Utilities</strong> — Metering plan, trench route/length, panel capacity, sewer depth <span class="badge">cost swing</span></li>
          <li><strong>Draw schedule</strong> — Deposits tied to real milestones (foundation, framing, rough-ins, finals)</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule realism</strong> — Gantt outline with permit lead time and inspection buffers</li>
          <li><strong>Change-orders</strong> — Who can approve, pricing method (fixed vs T&M), markup caps</li>
          <li><strong>Warranty & punchlist</strong> — Lengths for structure/MEP/finishes; day-zero punch process</li>
          <li><strong>Permit support</strong> — Who submits, pays, and responds to comments; resubmittal fees {{verify locally}}</li>
          <li><strong>References & photos</strong> — Two recent ADUs + one in-progress you can tour</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="note">Tip: Put this list into your RFQ email so every bidder answers the same questions.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap" id="compare">
      <h2>Prefab, panelized, design-build, or GC? Quick compare</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <table role="table" aria-label="ADU builder types comparison">
          <thead>
            <tr><th scope="col">Builder type</th><th scope="col">Strengths</th><th scope="col">Watch-outs</th><th scope="col">Best fit</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Prefab modules</strong></td>
              <td>Factory quality; predictable shell timeline</td>
              <td>Craning/site staging; utility hookups still local</td>
              <td>Access for crane, simpler lots</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Panelized</strong></td>
              <td>Faster dry-in than stick; flexible layouts</td>
              <td>Coordination on site still critical</td>
              <td>Moderate access; weather-sensitive sites</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Design-build</strong></td>
              <td>One team, fewer handoffs</td>
              <td>Less “bid competition” unless requested</td>
              <td>Owners who value coordination</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>General Contractor (GC)</strong></td>
              <td>Local subs, custom details</td>
              <td>Schedule depends on GC capacity</td>
              <td>Complex sites, custom specs</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="note">Speed vs paperwork: prefab/panelized often reduce site days, but you still need permits, inspections, and utility sign-offs.</p>
        <div class="bar" aria-hidden="true" style="margin-top:10px"><span style="width:68%"></span></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap" id="signals">
      <h2>Signals of a solid builder</h2>
      <div class="grid cols-2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Green flags</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Answers the 10-point checklist without hedging</li>
            <li>Offers site walk with utility talk (amps, sewer depth, trench path)</li>
            <li>Draw schedule tied to inspections, not vague “mobilization”</li>
            <li>Publishes change-order markup and response time</li>
            <li>Provides reference projects with similar access/lot type</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Red flags</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>“We’ll figure utilities later”</li>
            <li>Massive allowances with bargain placeholders</li>
            <li>No exclusions list; schedule is just a date range</li>
            <li>Only distant references or non-ADU work</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap" id="bids">
      <h2>How to run apples-to-apples bids (in 20 minutes)</h2>
      <div class="card grid cols-2">
        <div>
          <ol>
            <li>Send the same plan set and the 10-point checklist to 2–3 builders.</li>
            <li>Specify finish level (e.g., quartz counters, LVP flooring) and appliance package.</li>
            <li>State trench length assumptions (e.g., “~60 ft to sewer cleanout”).</li>
            <li>Request itemized pricing + contingency line (10–15%).</li>
            <li>Ask for proposed draw schedule and estimated permit timeline.</li>
            <li>Invite alternates (e.g., panel upgrade) priced add/alt, not buried.</li>
          </ol>
          <p class="note">Numbers are illustrative; verify fees, tap charges, and incentives with your city or utility. {{verify locally}}</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="card">
            <strong>Next step:</strong> lock a shortlist and book a site walk. After that, <a href="/estimate">share your ZIP and budget</a> and we’ll match you with reputable builders and lenders in your area.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap trust" id="cases">
      <h2>Mini case studies</h2>
      <figure class="card">
        <img src="/assets/hero-adu.jpg" alt="Detached ADU under construction with framed walls" />
        <figcaption><strong>750 sf detached, sloped lot.</strong> Panelized builder hit dry-in in two weeks; extra trenching added 4% to budget. Payback with rental: ~9–11 years (illustrative).</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="card">
        <img src="/assets/hero-adu.jpg" alt="Garage conversion ADU with upgraded windows and siding" />
        <figcaption><strong>420 sf garage conversion.</strong> Design-build GC handled permits; slab moisture mitigation added 2% but saved rework risk.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

